SUMMARIZER="D">      

More than 150 geophysical instruments in Japan's coastal Tokai region
tracks seismic activity, rock strain, crustal tilt, tidal movements
and ground water levels.  The data are telemetered to Tokyo where they
are monitored around the clock in the hope that experts there will
recognize unusual phenomena that may indicate an imminent earthquake.

Long after the rest of the world has abandoned hope of predicting
earthquakes, Japan continues to spend 2.5m dollars a year monitoring
the Tokai region and close to 100m dollars more on general earthquake
prediction research.

Skeptics say it is at best a misguided effort that wastes money and is
dangerously misleading to the public.</SUM>

<SUM
